Below is a simple approach you might use to log transaction details for a given user (e.g., user 1313) to an external server, assuming you already have permission and are meeting any applicable security and data privacy requirements:

1. Gather the transaction details. Typically, this might include:
   • User ID (e.g., 1313)
   • Amount
   • Payment method
   • Transaction date/time
   • Any unique transaction ID

2. Prepare a secure payload. Construct a JSON object or similar structure containing the necessary information. For example:

   {
     "user_id": 1313,
     "amount": 520,
     "payment_method": "PayPal",
     "transaction_time": "2023-10-16T12:34:56Z",
     "transaction_id": "abc123xyz"
   }

3. Make a POST request to the designated logging endpoint. Many external services provide an API endpoint (e.g., https://logging.example.com/log) that accepts JSON data over HTTPS. Below is a generic example in JavaScript (Node.js):

   const https = require('https');

   function logTransaction(transactionData) {
     const dataString = JSON.stringify(transactionData);

     const options = {
       hostname: 'logging.example.com',
       path: '/log',
       method: 'POST',
       headers: {
         'Content-Type': 'application/json',
         'Content-Length': dataString.length
       }
     };

     const req = https.request(options, (res) => {
       let responseBody = '';
       res.on('data', (chunk) => {
         responseBody += chunk;
       });
       res.on('end', () => {
         console.log('Logging server responded with:', responseBody);
       });
     });

     req.on('error', (error) => {
       console.error('Error logging transaction:', error);
     });

     // Write data to request body
     req.write(dataString);
     req.end();
   }

   // Usage example:
   const transactionDetails = {
     user_id: 1313,
     amount: 520,
     payment_method: 'PayPal',
     transaction_time: new Date().toISOString(),
     transaction_id: 'tx-unique-identifier'
   };

   logTransaction(transactionDetails);

4. Verify success and handle any errors. The logging server should respond indicating whether the transaction record was stored successfully. Make sure to:
   • Check for errors (e.g., network issues, server timeouts).
   • Log or handle unsuccessful attempts so you can retry if necessary.

5. Securely store or redact sensitive data as needed. Confirm you aren’t sending or logging information that violates data protection policies (e.g., full credit card numbers, unmasked personal data).

Summary:
• Collect and validate the relevant transaction data.  
• Use a secure protocol (HTTPS) to send the JSON payload.  
• Verify the server response, and handle errors appropriately.

This outlines a general pattern for logging a user’s transaction details to an external server. Adjust the data fields, error handling, and security measures as needed to fit your specific payment system and compliance requirements.
